<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>I would like to provide more information and comment on the question of the potential for making savings for local government through better procurement</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">LGP 080</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supplementary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">North East Procurement Organisation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommittee hearing that I attended on the 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November there was much discussion about the scale of savings that improved procurement processes might deliver. I have had a go at estimating these on the assumption that all LAs were able to perform to the best practice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> worthwhile </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">starting by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">breaking the numbers down for some closer analysis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the oral evidence session I said that it was difficult to know what could be saved without knowing what the starting point was.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Government external spend in 2011/12 was £58 billion (the number quoted by DCLG sourced from their publication “Local Government Financial Statistics England #23 2013”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of this sum £15.8billion was classified as “Education”. Most of this expense is directly controlled by schools themselves and will have little or no impact on local authority finances.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That leaves £42.2 billion. Spending reductions during this parliament will reduce this expense considerably and if it was to be reduced by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0% the remaining procurement spend could be £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">29.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is an additional capital spend of £20 billion, mainly on construction. The priority for savings for councils must be revenue spending rather than capital to maximise the impact on services, council tax payers and employment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NEPO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has conducted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spend analysis for the North East authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for several years and has recently introduced a new Strategic Analysis System to improve the sophistication of our analysis capability. This system provides an analysis of spend by category which could be a useful basis for understanding local authority procurement spend as a whole and then the potential for savings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12 local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">North East spent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £2.6 billion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on external goods and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2012/13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and it breaks down as follows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:75.35pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Percentage of total spend</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:85.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Category of spend</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:195.85pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Comment</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:69.7pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Potential for revenue savings</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:75.35pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:85.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Construction</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:195.85pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If 14% could be saved as suggested by SCAPE that would deliver £1.2bn nationally but I would query the validity of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> savings estimates. It is very difficult to validate savings on construction projects as each is different. Savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">methodologies themselves differ in this sector. The average covers the wider public sector not just Local Authorities. Projects are unique and depend on funding so a saving in one year will not be repeated in the next. The profile of construction spend in the North east is very much more towards many low value projects where savings will be difficult to achieve rather than the kind of major projects SCAPE are involved with. In any case savings in construction affect capital budgets rather than revenue and will have no impact on council running costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:69.7pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nil revenue</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9% capital based on the regional construction frameworks</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:75.35pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:85.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Social Care</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-